    <pre>Hi Paul,

Asheesh asked me to have a look at this. It looks like a bunch of this conversation happened on 
IRC, which makes it hard for me to understand the state in this thread, but here's at least some 
feedback:

&gt; 2. Q: Why _should_ I handle the validation differently? Why is it sub-optimal?

It's sub-optimal because we shouldn't roll our own way of validating e-mail addresses that 
penalizes addresses containing certain keywords when there are existing, correct ways of validating 
e-mail addresses.

&gt; really what is stopping someone typing in _any_ valid email address?

The question to ask, then, is if you actually care about verifying what `git config user.email` is set 
to. You're right -- we can never know that they are using their correct address, and if that's the only 
valuable test then we just shouldn't test it and move on.

&gt; So why are you telling me... "I would also assert that the mission step hasn't been
&gt; successfully completed, or some other deeper check."  when the actual test _is_
&gt; asserting that the mission step hasn't been completed? eg:
&gt; "self.assertFalse(controllers.mission_completed(paulproteus, 'git_config'))" @
&gt; line #71.

I think Asheesh just didn't see in the moment that this function was called from a test that does 
make that check.

Paul: thanks a ton for all the work you've been doing on OpenHatch. I'm sorry you are getting 
frustrated with the back and forth of reviews, but stick with it. Also, you might find it satisfying to 
work on some smaller tickets for a bit, for the satisfaction of closing out a bunch without so much 
back and forth.

I'll keep this in review so Asheesh can comment on Q1, which seems to have been discussed on IRC. 
`self.client` is used exclusively over a local `client` in mysite/missions/git/tests.py, so I don't 
understand Asheesh's comment either (but I also only skimmed the file).</pre>
