  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>I can't accept the "git config" tests yet because of this:

+    def test_do_git_description_mission_incorrectly(self):
+        self.assertFalse(self.email_address_is_rejected('<a href="mailto:paulproteus@pathi.local">paulproteus@pathi.local</a>'))

You seem to assert that <a href="mailto:paulproteus@pathi.local">paulproteus@pathi.local</a> should *not* be rejected
(assertFalse + the method name). That strikes me as incorrect; it should *be*
rejected.

Also, in "def email_address_is_rejected", checking the status code is a good
first step, but I would also assert that the mission step hasn't been
successfully completed, or some other deeper check.

Also, your test is kind of messy: You will reject any email address that has
"host" or "local" in it, but that means you'll reject "<a href="mailto:asheesh@mywebhost.com">asheesh@mywebhost.com</a>"
(for example) and "<a href="mailto:asheesh@localtv.com">asheesh@localtv.com</a>". As I think this through, I wonder: can
you just use the Django built-in EmailField to do the validation part? See also
<a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/ref/forms/fields/">https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/ref/forms/fields/</a>

I would suggest that you extract the email checking functionality into a
different function (probably, make it part of the def clean_email() in the
Django form you're using -- and actually, if you make it an EmailField, you can
use Django's built-in email checking)... actually, it *is* already an email
field! Hmm.

I would suggest you rewrite your email-validity-checks to use the Form class,
rather than the Django view, so that you can just straightforwardly check if the
form validation will accept e.g. pathi.local.

Also, in the template, rather than passing HTML in from the Python code, you
could just take the string the Python passes in and surround it as necessary
with HTML. For example, instead of

{{ var|safe|escape }}

maybe

&lt;strong&gt;{{ var|safe|escape }}&lt;/strong&gt;

Disabling the built-in Django escaping is something I don't like doing lightly,
but if in this case you need it and you know it's a safe thing to do, that's okay.

You're on the right track, and your git commit message is way clearer and easier
to read than they used to be!</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
