  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>Hi Paul,

I think I can see some things that are going wrong here. But first of all, can
you *please* submit your work in smaller fragments? For example, the fixes to
about_git.html don't have to be in the same massive commit as these other changes.

If you create smaller commits, then you can feel happy about the smaller pieces
of work that are definitely correct, but moreover I can deploy them
independently of other work that is not yet ready.

If you need help with the git tools in order to make smaller commits, I am quite
happy to provide it. It's quite possible to take an existing commit and separate
it out into different commits, and that would make both of our lives easier.

Okay, as for this test: here's what I said on IRC last night:

&lt;paulproteus&gt; I suspect self.client is not logged in
&lt;paulproteus&gt; use client = self.login_with_client()
&lt;paulproteus&gt; then client.post()
&lt;paulproteus&gt; Times like these, I often do 'print response' in the tests, to see
what it is

Have you tried doing 'print response' to see what exactly you're getting? You
said you're getting an HTTP 302; that's a redirect. That either means that the
view is asking the "client" to log in, or that the POST submission succeeded
without error.

In general, don't use self.client. Use a local variable in your test called
"client" that you get as a result of calling self.login_with_client().

Also, you have some English style issues: You wrote, "Now let's get Git setup"
but (for American English, at least) it should be "Now let's get Git set up".

Some other issues: In the patch, I see a change to the indenting of the
HttpResponseRedirect at the end of "def resetrepo". Why change the indenting?
You also seem to be mixing tabs and spaces, which is generally bad news for
Python code. Please just use spaces.

<a href="http://develop.participatoryculture.org/index.php/CodingStandards">http://develop.participatoryculture.org/index.php/CodingStandards</a> has some
generally high-quality code style guidelines. 

You're on the right track. I think that if you work to answer my questions about
logging the user in, you can get this finished. Let me know how it goes.</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
